Problem A


Problem 1

Plot the data and comment on relationship between insecticides (A, B, C), deposit and the proportion of killed insects


data(deposit)

ggplot(data=deposit, aes(Deposit, Killed/Number, colour = Insecticide)) +
  geom_point() 

deposit$A <- ifelse(deposit$Insecticide=="A", 1, 0) 
deposit$B <- ifelse(deposit$Insecticide=="B", 1, 0)
deposit$C <- ifelse(deposit$Insecticide=="C", 1, 0)


From the plot above that the number of insects killed increases as the amount of insecticide deposit increases. We also see that insecticide C kills a higher proportion of insects at every deopsit level in comparision to A and B.

Problem 3

Diagnose the model and identify if any influential observations exist

plot(bin)

# Cook's distance
plot(bin, which = 4, id.n = 3)
pchisq(48.026,14,lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 1.301603e-05


Hypothesis


\(H_0:\) The Model is Adequate \(H_1:\) The Model is not Adequate


Rejection Region

Reject \(H_0\) if \(p < \alpha\); \(\alpha = 0.05\)


We reject the null hypothesis, the output shown above indicates that the model is not adequate.


Based on the plot of Cooks Distance above, obs 6 is an extreme observation that we should consider for deletion.

Problem 5


Our model is as follows:


\({\hat{Killed/Number} = -4.4613 + 2.8875*log(Deposit) - 0.3489*B + 2.8402*C}\)


We can conclude that when Insecticide C is used the difference in logs of proportion of insects killed is expected to be 2.8402 higher, assuming all other variables are held constant. Similarly, when using Insecticide B, we expect the difference in logs to be -0.3489 lower.


Problem 6

Use Probit and Complementary-log-log link functions to fit the model. Plot and Compare the three models using AIC

plot(Killed/Number ~ Deposit, data=deposit,
     xlab="Deposit",
     ylab="Proportion of Insects Killed")
title(main="When C=1")


bin.probit <- update( bin2, family=binomial(link="probit") )
#using link function c-log-log
bin.cll <- update( bin2, family=binomial(link="cloglog") )

# compare the different coefficient
cfs=rbind( Logistic=coef(bin2), Probit=coef(bin.probit), CLL=coef(bin.cll))
cfs
##          (Intercept) log(Deposit)         B        C
## Logistic   -4.461346     2.887499 0.3489063 2.840178
## Probit     -2.623072     1.690049 0.2085553 1.672082
## CLL        -3.138015     1.714269 0.2492542 1.706162
cbind(cfs, Res.deviance=c(deviance(bin2), deviance(bin.probit), deviance(bin.cll)) )
##          (Intercept) log(Deposit)         B        C Res.deviance
## Logistic   -4.461346     2.887499 0.3489063 2.840178     23.38522
## Probit     -2.623072     1.690049 0.2085553 1.672082     22.34820
## CLL        -3.138015     1.714269 0.2492542 1.706162     36.46514
# FOR C=1
b = seq(0,8,length=18)
nB = 0
nC = 1

newdata=data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC)


logit=predict(bin2,newdata = data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC),type="response")
probit=predict(bin.probit,newdata = data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC),type="response")
loglog=predict(bin.cll,newdata = data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC),type="response")


lines(logit ~ b,col="black", lwd=2)
lines(probit ~ b, col="purple",lty=2,lwd=2)
lines(loglog ~ b,col="red",lty=4,lwd=2)
legend("topleft",lwd=2,lty = c(1,2,4),col = c("black","purple","red"),legend = c("Logit","Probit","c-log-log"))

#####

# FOR B=1
b = seq(0,8,length=18)
nB = 1
nC = 0

newdata=data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC)


logit2=predict(bin2,newdata = data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC),type="response")
probit2=predict(bin.probit,newdata = data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC),type="response")
loglog2=predict(bin.cll,newdata = data.frame(Deposit=b, B=nB, C=nC),type="response")


plot(Killed/Number ~ Deposit, data=deposit,
     main="When B=1",
     xlab="Deposit",
     ylab="Proportion of Insects Killed")
lines(logit2 ~ b,col="black", lwd=2)
lines(probit2 ~ b, col="purple",lty=2,lwd=2)
lines(loglog2 ~ b,col="red",lty=4,lwd=2)
legend("bottomright",lwd=2,lty = c(1,2,4),col = c("black","purple","red"),legend = c("Logit","Probit","c-log-log"))


Above we have the graphs of our logit, probit, complementary log log functions for Insecticide B and Insecticide C. We can see for all three different functions they follow similar paths with slight deviation. We also C kills a higher amount of insects, regardless of deposit level. This accurately reflects what we saw previously.

AIC(bin2)
## [1] 93.58276
AIC(bin.probit)
## [1] 92.54574
AIC(bin.cll)
## [1] 106.6627


From the output above, we see that model using the probit link function produces a slightly smaller AIC value in comparison to logit and complementary log-log, suggesting that it is a slightly better fit.

Problem 4

Interpret the best model

From the outputs seen in problem 3, we can conclude that our negative binomial model is the best, based on its low AIC value and \(p>\alpha\) for the residual deviance test. We can conclude that our model is adequate.


Our negative binomial regression model with coefficients can be seen below:

\({\hat{Crimes} = 8.762 - 0.0123595*Temp - 0.00000580*Income + 0.0833089*Unemployment + 0.0000005*Population}\)


From the summary output above, we see that only one predictor variable is statistically significant on 0.05 level of confidence, the population variable. We can interpret the population coefficient as follows: for a one unit change in the population, the odds of the number crimes is expected to increase by 5.377e-06, assuming all other predictors are held constant.
